questions.explanation:
Dereferencing `nullptr` is **undefined behavior**.

The pointer `p` holds address `0`. There is no valid memory there.
On most systems, this causes a **segmentation fault** (crash).

The compiler does not catch this. It is a runtime error.

Always check before using a pointer:
```cpp
if (p != nullptr) {
    std::cout << *p;
}
```

